Project Description¶

The objective of this project is to build a model that can predict extreme air quality emissions events based on the meteorology (temperature, wind speed and direction, humidity, precipitation) and measured pollutant concentrations at surrounding monitors. This is typically done using inverse chemical transport models, which are notoriously time intensive. The air quality community has long sought for a more efficient alternative method.

This project focuses on Richmond, CA, which is a city whose residents frequently breathe air that is described as "toxic soup". The city is home to oil refineries, chemical production plants, metal production facilities, shipping ports, and hazardous waste sites. Below is a map showing all toxic chemical emitting sites in Richmond:

Image from: https://richmondconfidential.org/2017/10/28/richmonds-toxics-2/

Using machine learning for air quality prediction is a field that is developing quickly. Studies are usually designed to predict air quality at one location (typically a sensitive receptor such as a school or park) based on air quality measured at several surrounding monitors and meteorological data. This project will tackle the inverse problem, where emissions in the area are predicted using the concentrations measured at several monitors. If successful, a model can take the place of methods such as chemical transport models (time intensive, difficult to set up and run).

The proposed model will use emissions, meteorological, and air quality monitoring data over two years from 2016 to 2017. The model will extract out extreme events (e.g. top 10% of measured concentrations at each monitor) and predict emissions for those events. Due to confidentiality issues the pollutant of interest and emission sources will be masked, but insights and physical interpretations will still be explained.

Research questions include:

  • Can a reasonably good emissions prediction model be built using the available datasets?
  • What are the most important features in predicting emissions?
  • Knowing nothing about the processes that emit the pollutant, can we make a prediction on what kinds of sources contribute to the emissions based on observations from other variables in the dataset?
  • How can the model be improved? What additional data would be most helpful to add?

Data Description¶

Emissions Data¶

  • Aggregated hourly emissions data from 20 different sources in Richmond will be used as features in the model. These 20 sources are the biggest emitters of the pollutant of interest for this model. This data is not available publicly.
  • This is the target variable for prediction.

Monitoring Data¶

  • Hazardous air pollutant and criteria air pollutant concentrations and meteorological data from three fenceline monitors, available on Richmond's fenceline monitoring website: https://www.richmondairmonitoring.org/measurements.html
  • Hazardous air pollutant and criteria air pollutant concentrations and meteorological data from four community air monitors, available on Richmond's community air monitoring website: https://opendata.ci.richmond.ca.us/stories/s/Air-Monitoring/jqp5-q3g4/

  • EPA/Bay Area AQMD air quality monitoring data for four stations in Richmond: https://aqs.epa.gov/aqsweb/documents/data_api.html

  • Measured air pollutants in the monitoring datasets include the following:

  • NH3: emitted from nitrogen products (fertilizer), biogenic sources
  • H2S: emitted from sulfur products, landfills
  • BC: emitted from diesel combustion
  • PM25: various sources, most common is wind blown dust
  • SO2: emitted from combustion of sulfur impurities in products, such as coal or petroleum

Meteorological Data¶

The monitoring data has temperature, wind speed/direction, and humidity at each station, but extra data sources are needed to gather precipitation, solar insolation, and ceiling height (height of the lowest clouds):

  • Precipitation from City of Richmond: http://cdec.water.ca.gov/dynamicapp/QueryF?s=RHL&d=31-Dec-2017+23:39&span=8760hours
  • Solar radiation from NREL: https://maps.nrel.gov/nsrdb-viewer
  • Ceiling height from NCDC, Oakland Airport station: https://www7.ncdc.noaa.gov/CDO/cdopoemain.cmd?datasetabbv=DS3505

Dispersion Modeling Data¶

An important factor in air quality modeling is terrain and the location of emissions sources and monitoring stations relative to each other, which is not accounted for in any of the three data sources listed above. To account for this, outputs from a quick model run of EPA's AERMOD dispersion model is used as an input.

Data Retrieval, Cleaning, and EDA¶

Emissions Data¶

Aggregated emissions data for all sources within the area is provided by the local air agency. This data is not available publicly. We'll call the pollutant that this emission rate corresponds to pollutant "X".

This file contains 17544 hours (8760 in 2017, 8784 hours in 2016 since it was a leap year) worth of aggregated emissions data. Visualizing a timeseries of hourly emission rates of "X" below:

[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2058263dbe0>]

We can see that emissions are very sporadic, with some extreme events scattered randomly throughout. This is common in many air quality analyses, and is characteristic of equipment malfunctions or sudden throughput increases amid routine service.

In [7]:

Out[7]:

In [8]:
emis.emisrate.skew()
Out[8]:
2.656924870568949

The distribution appears to be bimodal and positively skewed, so keep in mind that this may need some sort of transform to a normal distribution as the target variable before training the model. We will end up filtering the dataset for the top 10% measurements of SO2 concentrations at each monitor, so the filtered dataset's distribution may change.

Dispersion Modeling Data¶

Dispersion modeling is commonly used in air quality analysis to determine the fate and transport of pollutants. It takes the locations of sources and receptors, meteorology, and terrain of the area into account. The number resulting from the dispersion model output represents the "strength" attributed to each source at each receptor (in this case, each monitor). A higher number indicates that the meteorology and terrain are favorable in transporting pollutants from a given source to a specific monitor.

US EPA's AERMOD dispersion model was used to produce these outputs. Inputs to the model included the locations of each source, locations of each monitor, and default EPA meteorlogy and terrain data. The purpose of including these outputs in the machine learning model is to feed the model features that take terrain and transport into account.

Model outputs were outputted and saved as a pickle file:

In [9]:
df_aermod = pd.read_pickle("data/aermod_out.pkl")

The contents of this dataframe are difficult to decipher, so I'll explain below:

  • Aside from the DATE column, each column represents the hourly source-receptor "strength". The source is represented by the first substring ahead of the first underscore, and the receptor (i.e., monitor) code is represented by the second substring.
  • There are 6 different sources, numbered from S1 through S6.
  • Of the receptors (monitors), there are two UV fencelines represented by 31 receptors (21 receptors in fenceline UV1, 10 receptors in fenceline UV2), three community monitoring stations (CMS1 through CMS3), and three ground level monitors (GLM1 through GLM3).
  • The dataframe lists a source-receptor "strength" between each source and monitor.
  • Source-receptor strengths of zero or close to zero indicate that transport of pollutants from the given source to the given monitor is not favorable during that hour, i.e. winds are blowing in the opposite direction or terrain obstructs the flow.

There is a lot to look through here, but basic information you can infer from this includes:

  • Average source-receptor strength is the highest between UV fenceline #1 and source #5. It's likely that these two are located very close to each other.
  • Generally, the UV fenceline and GLM source-receptor strengths are higher than the CMS receptor strengths. This is because the CMS monitors are further away from the emissions sources.

Graphical EDA: define a function that will be used in this notebook to produce a Seaborn distplot for each feature:

In [12]:
def distplots(df, cols, ncol_plot=3):
    nrow_plot = int(np.ceil(len(cols)/ncol_plot))
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrow_plot, ncol_plot, figsize=(16,16/ncol_plot*nrow_plot))
    r = 0
    c = 0
    for col in cols:
        sns.distplot(df[col], ax=ax[r,c], kde=False)
        ax[r,c].set_title(col)
        c += 1
        if c == ncol_plot:
            c = 0
            r += 1
In [13]:
distplots(df_aermod, [col for col in df_aermod.columns if col != "DATE"])

These features are very skewed and will definitely need a Box-Cox transformation down the line. I will leave this data as is for now, and perform any transformations or additional analysis on the full input dataframe later.

Monitoring Data¶

Unlike the emissions and dispersion modeling data, the monitoring data is still in a very raw state and will need significant processing. The monitoring data will come from 4 different sources:

  • cms.pkl: pollutant concentration and meteorological data from three community monitoring stations (CMS), previously read in via private API and saved as a pickle.
  • uv.pkl: pollutant concentration and meteorological data from three UV fenceline monitors (UV), previously read in via private API and saved as a pickle.
  • glm.pkl: pollutant concentration from three ground level monitors (GLM), previously read in via private API and saved as a pickle.
  • EPA data from two Bay Area Air Quality Management District monitoring stations, available publicly via API.

First, let's load in and look at the community monitoring station (CMS) and UV fenceline (UV) data:

In [14]:

The format for the name of each column is described below:

  • The first substring before the underscore is what is being measured, the second substring is the name of the monitor.
  • NH3, H2S, BC, PM25, and SO2 are all pollutant concentration measurements. Emissions of each of these pollutants originate from different sources, and all five pollutants are intended to be a "proxy" for the activity at each measurement. For example, an interval with high BC concentrations may indicate that a heavy-duty truck had just passed on the monitor. Note that the emission rate that the model will predict is not one of these five pollutants. In other words, we are attempting to predict an emission rate for a pollutant that is not in the input dataset.
  • WD = wind direction, WS = wind speec, HUM = humidity, TEMP = temperature. Meteorological variables are important in considering the atmospheric conditions and transport.

More on the pollutants in this dataset:

  • NH3: emitted from chemical processes involving nitrogen, such as oil refining, fertilizer production, or landfills.
  • H2S: emitted from chemical processes involving sulfur, such as sulfur production.
  • BC: emitted from combustion sources, mostly heavy-duty diesel trucks. Typically higher closer to roadways.
  • PM25: emitted from combustion or fugitive dust sources, typically higher closer to roadways.
  • SO2: emitted from combustion of sulfur products, such as from oil refining or mobile sources.

For accounting purposes later on, replace all -999 with NaN. Values of -999 indicate missing data in this dataset.

In [19]:
cms_uv = cms_uv.replace(-999, np.nan)

Transform wind speed and direction into x and y components, with 0 degrees as north to south. With this orientation, wind speeds in the x- and y-directions need to be multiplied by -1.

In [20]:
stations = ['CMS1','CMS2','CMS3','UV1','UV2','UV3']
for station in stations:
    cms_uv['WS_X_'+station] = cms_uv['WS_'+station]*np.sin(np.pi/180*cms_uv['WD_'+station])*-1
    cms_uv['WS_Y_'+station] = cms_uv['WS_'+station]*np.cos(np.pi/180*cms_uv['WD_'+station])*-1

Get rid of the initial WS and WD columns, since all of the information is now in the WS_X and WS_Y columns:

In [21]:
cms_uv = cms_uv.drop(columns=['WD_'+x for x in stations])
cms_uv = cms_uv.drop(columns=['WS_'+x for x in stations])

Since all 6 stations are in the vicinity of each other, temperature and humidity will essentially be the same across all stations. Aggregate the temperature and RH features into one (average across all 6 stations) and drop the original columns:

In [22]:
temp_cols = ['TEMP_'+x for x in stations]
rh_cols = ['HUM_'+x for x in stations]
cms_uv['TEMP'] = cms_uv[temp_cols].mean(axis=1)
cms_uv['RH'] = cms_uv[rh_cols].mean(axis=1)
cms_uv = cms_uv.drop(columns=temp_cols)
cms_uv = cms_uv.drop(columns=rh_cols)

Fill in missing values:

  • Concentrations: fill with detection limits from air quality monitor's manufacturer. Missing values likely mean that the concentration in air was too low to detect.
  • Temp and RH: interpolate between values. Assuming a linear form between temperature and humidity from one interval to the next is a typical assumption in filling in these values.
  • WS: first check if corresponding station from other monitoring has data (i.e. if CMS1 is missing but UV1 has data, fill in with the CMS1 value). The number corresponding to each station indiciates the general region it is in (i.e. CMS1 and UV1 are near each other, CMS2 and UV2 are also near each other).

Fill in missing concentrations with detection limits:

In [25]:
dl = {'NH3':1, 'H2S':1, 'BC':0, 'PM25':3, 'SO2':5}
for pol in dl.keys():
    pol_cols = [col for col in cms_uv.columns if col.startswith(pol)]
    for col in pol_cols:
        cms_uv[col] = cms_uv[col].fillna(dl[pol])

Interpolate to fill in missing temperatures and relative humidities:

In [26]:
cms_uv['TEMP'] = cms_uv['TEMP'].interpolate()
cms_uv['RH'] = cms_uv['RH'].interpolate()

Grab corresponding values from other monitoring stations to fill in missing WS:

In [27]:
ws_cms_cols = [col for col in cms_uv.columns if (col.startswith('WS') and 'CMS' in col)]
ws_uv_cols = [col for col in cms_uv.columns if (col.startswith('WS') and 'UV' in col)]
for col in ws_cms_cols:
    cms_uv[col] = cms_uv[col].fillna(cms_uv[col.replace('CMS','UV')])
for col in ws_uv_cols:
    cms_uv[col] = cms_uv[col].fillna(cms_uv[col.replace('UV','CMS')])

All good now, let's do some graphical EDA as a reality check:

In [31]:
plot_cols = [col for col in cms_uv.columns if ("CMS" in col or "UV" in col)]
distplots(cms_uv, plot_cols)

Again some very skewed features which will need a transformation before model training. This makes sense for the data though - air quality measurements are usually positively skewed, since most measurements are at a "baseline" with some extreme events mixed in.

It's possible that the majority of readings are at the detection limit, or in other words, too low for the instruments to measure. Let's see what percentage of measurements are actually above the DL:

In [32]:
cms_pollutants = ['NH3','H2S','BC','PM25']
cms_stations = ['CMS1','CMS2','CMS3']
for pol in cms_pollutants:
    for st in cms_stations:
        col = pol+"_"+st
        pct_complete = cms_uv.loc[cms_uv[col] > dl[pol]].shape[0]/cms_uv.shape[0]
        print(col + ": " + str(round(pct_complete*100,1)) + "% complete")

uv_stations = ['UV1','UV2','UV3']

    col = "SO2_"+st
    pct_complete = cms_uv.loc[cms_uv[col] > dl['SO2']].shape[0]/cms_uv.shape[0]

SO2_UV1: 2.9% complete
SO2_UV2: 6.7% complete
SO2_UV3: 5.1% complete

It is important to note that the majority of data points for H2S and SO2 are reading at the detection limit. It is common in air quality analysis to select only the top X percent of events for model analysis, so this may not be an issue in the end, just something to keep in mind at the moment. We may end up selecting the top X percent of events from one of the SO2 UV stations (or with the low percentages we have, just the number of hits), and using that to train the model.

How do the pollutant concentration measurements correlate with each other? This may give a better idea of which pollutants are emitted together by the same process, and which are emitted by different processes.

In [36]:
def corr_matrix(df, num_cols, figsize=(15,15)):
    df_corrs = df[num_cols].corr().round(2)
    mask = np.zeros_like(df_corrs, dtype=np.bool)
    mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(df_corrs, annot=df_corrs, mask=mask, center=0, linewidths=.5, cbar=False)
In [37]:
corr_matrix(cms_uv, pol_cols)

There are a few cases where the same pollutant measurements from different stations correlate well with each other (e.g. PM25_CMS1 with PM25_CMS2), but cross-pollutant correlations all look weak. The exception may be BC with PM25, which is not surprising since BC is a subset of PM25. This suggests that different processes are responsible for the emission of each pollutant.

One thing to watch out for in timeseries data is baseline drift, where the baseline measurement drifts upward or downwards over time, biasing the actual measurements. An easy way to detect this is to plot timeseries of pollutant measurements.

NH3:

In [38]:

Baseline looks steady, and we see some interesting trends in H2S. One important note is that this data is in 5-minute intervals, but all other data that we are working with is hourly. To reduce this dataset from 5-minute to hourly resolution and to retain as much information as possible, create features for the average, maximum, and variance within each hour:

Note that wind speed is tricky to take the max of, since the sign (positive/negative) depends on the direction. Since we want maximum wind speed to represent the maximum magnitude, first take the absolute value of all wind speed columns before taking the hourly maximum:

In [43]:
cms_uv_ws_abs = cms_uv.copy()
ws_cols = [col for col in cms_uv.columns if col.startswith('WS')]
for col in ws_cols:
    cms_uv_ws_abs[col] = cms_uv_ws_abs[col].apply(lambda x:abs(x))
cms_uv_hourly_avg = cms_uv.groupby(['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']).mean().reset_index()
cms_uv_hourly_max = cms_uv_ws_abs.groupby(['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']).max().reset_index()
cms_uv_hourly_var = cms_uv.groupby(['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']).var().reset_index()
cms_uv_hourly_avg = cms_uv_hourly_avg.drop(columns=['MINUTE'])
cms_uv_hourly_max = cms_uv_hourly_max.drop(columns=['MINUTE','ACTUALDATE'])
cms_uv_hourly_var = cms_uv_hourly_var.drop(columns=['MINUTE'])
cms_uv_hourly_avg.columns = np.where(cms_uv_hourly_avg.columns.isin(['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']),cms_uv_hourly_avg.columns,cms_uv_hourly_avg.columns+'_AVG')
cms_uv_hourly_max.columns = np.where(cms_uv_hourly_max.columns.isin(['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']),cms_uv_hourly_max.columns,cms_uv_hourly_max.columns+'_MAX')
cms_uv_hourly_var.columns = np.where(cms_uv_hourly_var.columns.isin(['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']),cms_uv_hourly_var.columns,cms_uv_hourly_var.columns+'_VAR')
In [44]:
print(cms_uv_hourly_avg.shape)
print(cms_uv_hourly_max.shape)
print(cms_uv_hourly_var.shape)

(17522, 33)
(17522, 33)
(17522, 33)

There are 22 missing hours (17522 out of 17544, we can address later after merging the entire dataframe with the other datasets (they will show up as NaN in the merged dataframe).

Now that the CMS and UV monitoring data is cleaned up, let's move on to the ground level monitors (GLM). Similar to the CMS and UV data, this data was read in via private API and saved as a pickle file beforehand. The GLMs only measure SO2.

This dataset has SO2 measurements at 4 different GLMs from August 2014 through the end of 2017. We only need 2016-2017. First parse out individual columns for year, month, day, and hour. In [47]:

glm['JDAY'] = pd.to_numeric(glm['JDAY'])
glm = glm[glm.YEAR.isin([2016,2017])].reset_index(drop=True)

Our last set of data is from the Bay Area Air Quality Management District stations, which can be downloaded from EPA's API. The URL is edited for a specific pollutant code (in this case, SO2), station ID, and state ID.

In [61]:
def load_aqs_json(year, site_id):
    json_url = 'https://aqs.epa.gov/data/api/sampleData/bySite?email=test@aqs.api&key=test&param=42401&bdate='+str(year)+'0101&edate='+str(year)+'1231&state=06&county=013&site='+site_id
    with urllib.request.urlopen(json_url) as url:
        aqs_json = json.loads(url.read().decode())
    return pd.DataFrame.from_dict(aqs_json['Data'])

It seems ok to interpolate, but this dataset will need some baseline adjustment. First interpolate to fill NaNs:

In [71]:
aqs1 = aqs1.interpolate()
aqs2 = aqs2.interpolate()

The AQS1 dataset has a small interval where the baseline drops below 0, which needs to be adjusted upwards to the monitor's detection limit of 0.5. The AQS2 dataset requires more baseline adjustment, as noticeable drift is seen throughout the timeseries.

Peakutils has a function to estimate the baseline of a data interval, which is represented by an n-degree polynomial (the value of n is an input to the function). Use this to create a function for baseline adjustment:

  • Inputs to the function are the full dataframe needing baseline adjustment, the timesplits that represent the start and end of a single baseline drift, and the baseline value (e.g. detection limit).
  • One timesplit interval is needed for each segment where the baseline drifts differently. For example if the baseline drifts upwards and then downwards, two separate timesplits would be needed for baseline adjustment. The peakutils baseline function estimates an n-degree polynomial to represent the drifting baseline for each segment.
In [72]:
import peakutils
def baseline_corr(df, col, timesplits, base=0.5):
    '''Performs baseline correction on a certain column (col) in a dataframe (df).
       Correction done using a 2-degree polynomial baseline fit for each timesplit defined by the user.'''
    n=0
    Y_new = []
    X_new = []
    df = df.reset_index()
    for start,stop in timesplits:
        n += 1
        start = start
        stop = stop
        if n == len(timesplits):
            time_mask = (df['DATETIME'] <= stop) & (df['DATETIME'] >= start)
        else:
            time_mask = (df['DATETIME'] < stop) & (df['DATETIME'] >= start)
        X = df[(time_mask)]['DATETIME'].values
        Y = df[(time_mask)][col].values

        # Correction baseline is the fitted baseline minus the baseline value
        df_base = peakutils.baseline(Y,2) - base

        # segY is the measurement with corrected baseline
        segX = X
        segY = Y - df_base
        Y_new.extend(segY)
        X_new.extend(segX)

    # create new dataframe
    df_new = pd.DataFrame({'DATETIME':X_new , col: Y_new})
    df_new = df_new.set_index('DATETIME')
    return df_new

Define the timesplit intervals for the AQS1 data. We only need to smooth out the segment in the middle where the baseline drops below 1.

In [73]:
timestart = pd.to_datetime("2016-01-01 00:00")

It would make the most sense to interpolate for the averages. First sort the dataframe on HOUR/DAY/MONTH, then interpolate. Use plots to make sure the date has been sorted correctly:

In [87]:
monitor_df = monitor_df.sort_values(by=['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR']).reset_index(drop=True)
plt.plot(monitor_df.MONTH)
Out[87]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2ebdae07208>]
In [88]:
plt.plot(monitor_df.DAY)
Out[88]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2ebd45702b0>]
In [89]:
avg_cols = [col for col in monitor_df.columns if col.endswith("AVG")]
max_cols = [col for col in monitor_df.columns if col.endswith("MAX")]
for col in avg_cols:
    monitor_df[col] = monitor_df[col].interpolate()
for col in max_cols:
    monitor_df[col] = monitor_df[col].interpolate()

Replace NA in the VAR columns with zeros - this also indicates that the AVG for these columns were filled in with interpolation, or that the VAR is actually zero since there was just one sample:

In [90]:
var_cols = [col for col in monitor_df.columns if col.endswith("VAR")]
for col in var_cols:
    monitor_df[col] = monitor_df[col].fillna(0)

Skewness may be an issue with many of the variables that needs to be addressed later - especially for variance, lots of the values end up being close to 0.

Meteorological Data (precip, solar radiation, cloud cover, ceiling height)¶

Meteorological data has an important effect on air pollutant concentrations. Precipitation typically washes pollution out of the atmosphere, while more cloud cover and a lower ceiling height decreases the mixing volume, which increases the pollutant concentrations.

In [93]:
precip = pd.read_csv("data/Precip_Richmond.csv")
cloud = pd.read_csv("data/OAK_Airport_NCDC.csv")
solar = pd.read_csv("data/Solar_Richmond.csv")

Precipitation data¶

First look at precip data, parse out datetime string:

In [94]:
precip = precip.rename(columns={'DATE / TIMEPST':'DT', 'RAINTIP INCHES':'RAINTIP'})
precip.head()
Out[94]:
DT RAINTIP
0 01/01/2016 00:00 7.41
1 01/01/2016 01:00 7.41
2 01/01/2016 02:00 7.41
3 01/01/2016 03:00 7.41
4 01/01/2016 04:00 7.41
In [95]:
precip['MONTH'] = precip['DT'].str[:2].astype(int)
precip['DAY'] = precip['DT'].str[3:5].astype(int)
precip['YEAR'] = precip['DT'].str[6:10].astype(int)
precip['HOUR'] = precip['DT'].str[11:13].astype(int)
precip = precip.drop(columns='DT')
In [96]:
precip.head()
Out[96]:
RAINTIP MONTH DAY YEAR HOUR
0 7.41 1 1 2016 0
1 7.41 1 1 2016 1
2 7.41 1 1 2016 2
3 7.41 1 1 2016 3
4 7.41 1 1 2016 4

Hourly precip is equal to the difference in raintip between two hours:

In [97]:
precip['PRECIP'] = precip['RAINTIP'].diff().fillna(0)
In [98]:
precip.head()
Out[98]:
RAINTIP MONTH DAY YEAR HOUR PRECIP
0 7.41 1 1 2016 0 0.0
1 7.41 1 1 2016 1 0.0
2 7.41 1 1 2016 2 0.0
3 7.41 1 1 2016 3 0.0
4 7.41 1 1 2016 4 0.0

Something weird is going on, it looks like the raintip reset to 0 in the middle of the year. Just set this inflection point to 0, as if the raintip didn't change. The between hour difference should remain the same throughout.

In [99]:
plt.plot(precip.RAINTIP)
Out[99]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2ebd7e89390>]
In [100]:
plt.plot(precip.PRECIP)
Out[100]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2ebe9e7c780>]
In [101]:
precip['PRECIP'] = precip['PRECIP'].apply(lambda x:0 if x < 0 else x)
In [102]:
plt.plot(precip.PRECIP)
Out[102]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2ebd91962e8>]

This is a typical trend for annual precipitation - the wet season is in fall/winter, and the dry season is in summer.

Looks more reasonable now, drop the RAINTIP column and finalize the precip dataset:

In [103]:
precip = precip.drop(columns='RAINTIP')
precip.head()
Out[103]:
MONTH DAY YEAR HOUR PRECIP
0 1 1 2016 0 0.0
1 1 1 2016 1 0.0
2 1 1 2016 2 0.0
3 1 1 2016 3 0.0
4 1 1 2016 4 0.0
In [104]:
precip.shape
Out[104]:
(22825, 5)

There are some hours with multiple data points, since we are measuring the difference in raintip it's appropriate to just groupby and sum over individual hours.

In [105]:
precip = precip.groupby(['MONTH','DAY','YEAR','HOUR']).sum().reset_index()
precip.shape
Out[105]:
(17214, 5)
In [106]:
plt.plot(precip.PRECIP)
Out[106]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x2ebd73a4dd8>]

There are now hours with missing values, but we can merge on another dataframe later and fill in the NA with zeros.

Solar data¶

Keep only the columns that matter:

  • Datetime (need to reformat)
  • CLG (cloud ceiling height in hundreds of feet, 722 = unlimited)
  • SKC (cloud cover, CLR = clear; SCT = scattered, 1/8 to 4/8; BKN = broken, 5/8 to 7/8; OVC = overcast; OBS = obscured; POB = partial obscuration)
  • STP (station pressure)
In [113]:

Delete the original DATE column, and subtract 1 from HOUR to match it up with other dataframes (hour goes from 0-23, rather than 1-24):

Almost there - introduce a couple of new features for time, including weekend (0 = not weekend, 1 = weekend), and the sine and cosine of Julian day to help capture any seasonal variability. This is a common feature in many air quality studies. These functions connect the similarity between December and January across years.

In [139]:
df_ml['DATETIME'] = pd.to_datetime(dict(year=df_ml.YEAR,month=df_ml.MONTH,day=df_ml.DAY))
df_ml['JDAY'] = df_ml['DATETIME'].dt.strftime('%j')
df_ml['JDAY'] = pd.to_numeric(df_ml.JDAY,errors='coerce')
df_ml['DAYOFWEEK'] = df_ml['DATETIME'].dt.dayofweek+1
df_ml['WEEKEND'] = df_ml['DAYOFWEEK'].apply(lambda x:1 if x>5 else 0)
df_ml['SIN_JDAY'] = np.sin(2*math.pi*df_ml['JDAY']/365)
df_ml['COS_JDAY'] = np.cos(2*math.pi*df_ml['JDAY']/365)

All good, now save the full dataframe as a pickle for easy access later:

df_ml.to_pickle("data/df_ml.pkl")

Transformations¶

As we saw from plotting the distributions of each feature, we need to address the skewness. Apply a Box-Cox transformation to each feature, and save the lambda values so an inverse operation can be done later if needed. Also drop the time features, since those are not needed anymore.

Model Training¶

As mentioned in the project description, in air quality modeling and prediction we typically only care about the most extreme events. EPA and local state ambient air quality standards look at only the top 1% or 3% of top modeled or measured concentrations in determining compliance with the standards. Given the size of the dataset, I expanded this threshold to the top 10% of concentration readings at each monitor (top 1% or 3% would filter out too much of the data). Also by expanding the threshold, we are able to show that emissions can be predicted for a wider range of concentration readings (i.e., the model is more widely applicable to different physical conditions).

The workflow here will be as follows:

  • For each of 7 monitors (4 ground level monitors, 3 UV fenceline monitors), filter the dataset for the top 10% of hits (i.e., for a 17544 hour dataset spanning 2016-2017, select the top 1754 hours and use that for model fitting).
  • Use a 70/30 train/test split on the data.
  • For each monitor, use 4 different regression models to predict aggregated emissions from nearby sources: Ridge, Random Forests, XGBoost, Neural Networks. These are the most commonly tested models in air quality machine learning studies - typically Ridge performs the worst and serves as a "baseline" for how simple regression models do, and RF/XGB/NN do a lot better.
  • For regression/RF/XGB, store the regression coefficients/feature importances to look at after training for physical intuition.
  • Store the R^2 score for each model fitting to the test set as a metric of performance.

Last note: since SO2 is the best proxy for our "mystery pollutant" since they are usually emitted by the same processes (combustion of impurities in coal or petroleum), we will use SO2 concentrations to filter our dataset for the top 10%.

Define function for R^2 to be used with Keras NN model:

In [144]:
def r2(X, y, model):
    y = np.array(y).reshape((y.shape[0],1))
    RSS = np.sum(np.square(y-np.array(model.predict(X))))
    TSS = np.sum(np.square(y-np.mean(y)))
    return (1-RSS/TSS)

All-purpose function for model fitting, comments in code block below:

In [145]:
def create_model(X, y, model_type, pca_apply = False):
    '''
    X = dataframe of all features
    y = dataframe of target variable
    model_type = name of model type, defined in code below
    pca_apply = option to apply PCA for ridge regression
    '''
    # Use a 70/30 train/test split 
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.3,random_state=0)
    
    # Empty dataframes/dictionaries to store results
    scores = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Train_R2','Test_R2'])
    
    # Create object for model type based on input, which should be one of four options:
    # Ridge: Ridge linear regression, using K=10 cross validation to select the best alpha
    # RF: Random Forests (assuming default n_estimators of 100)
    # XGB: Extreme Gradient Boosting (assuming default n_estimators of 100)
    # NN: Neural Networks using Keras (assuming a 500 unit layer --> 20% dropout --> 100 unit layer --> 20% dropout)
    if model_type == "Ridge":
        alphas = [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100]
        model = RidgeCV(alphas=alphas, normalize=True, cv=10)
    elif model_type == "RF":
        model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100)
    elif model_type == "XGB":
        model = XGBRegressor(n_estimators=100, objective='reg:squarederror')
    elif model_type == "NN":
        model = Sequential()
        model.add(Dense(500, input_dim=X.shape[1], activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(0.2))
        model.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(0.2))
        model.add(Dense(1))
        model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
        
    # Model fitting for all model types
    if model_type == "Ridge":
        if pca_apply:
            pca = PCA()
            X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
            X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test)
            pca = PCA(n_components=np.argwhere(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_) > 0.999)[0][0])
            X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
            X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test)
            model.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)
            train_score = model.score(X_train_pca, y_train)
            test_score = model.score(X_test_pca, y_test)
            scores = scores.append({'Train_R2':train_score, 'Test_R2':test_score}, ignore_index=True)
        else:
            model.fit(X_train, y_train)
            train_score = model.score(X_train, y_train)
            test_score = model.score(X_test, y_test)
            scores = scores.append({'Train_R2':train_score, 'Test_R2':test_score}, ignore_index=True)
    elif model_type == "NN":
        model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=500, batch_size=X_train.shape[0], verbose=False, validation_data=(X_test,y_test))
        train_score = r2(X_train, y_train, model)
        test_score = r2(X_test, y_test, model)
        scores = scores.append({'Train_R2':train_score, 'Test_R2':test_score}, ignore_index=True)
    else:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        train_score = model.score(X_train, y_train)
        test_score = model.score(X_test, y_test)
        scores = scores.append({'Train_R2':train_score, 'Test_R2':test_score}, ignore_index=True)
        
    # For Ridge, store the fitted coefficients
    # For RF and XGB, store the feature importances
    if model_type == "Ridge":
        if not pca_apply:
            coefs = pd.DataFrame()
            coefs['feature'] = X_train.columns
            coefs['coef'] = model.coef_
            coefs = coefs.sort_values('coef', ascending=False)
            imp = coefs
            y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
        else:
            y_pred = model.predict(X_test_pca)
    elif model_type == "NN":
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
        imp = pd.DataFrame()
    else:
        imp = pd.DataFrame()
        imp['feature'] = X_train.columns
        imp['importance'] = model.feature_importances_
        imp = imp.sort_values('importance', ascending=False)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    return scores, imp, y_pred, y_test

Function creates a full pipeline for model training and testing:

  • Filters data for the top 10% of hits (90th percentile and above)
  • Performs a Box-Cox transformation on the dataframe of predictors
  • Merges on emissions dataframe to get rows corresponding to the top 10% of hits, then separates out the dataframes back into separate sets
  • Scales the dataframe of predictors (X)
  • Creates separate source groupings for emissions totals based on the input to the function
  • Calls the previously created "create_model" function for model fitting and scoring
  • Returns a dataframe of all test_scores for all combinations
In [146]:
def model_pipeline(df, emis_df, monitors, model_types):
    '''
    df = dataframe of all features
    emis_df = dataframe of emissions
    monitors = selected monitors, must match column names in df
    model_type = model type to be used in create_model function
    '''
    test_scores = pd.DataFrame(index=monitors, columns=[col+"_R2" for col in model_types])
    coefs_dict = {}
    y_preds_dict = {}
    y_tests_dict = {}
    for monitor in monitors:
        so2_threshold = np.percentile(df[monitor],90)
        df_filter = df.copy()
        df_filter = df_filter.loc[df_filter[monitor] > so2_threshold]
        for feature in df_filter.columns:
            if feature not in ['DATETIME','YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR','JDAY','DAYOFWEEK','WEEKEND','SIN_JDAY','COS_JDAY','year','month','day','hour']:
                if df_filter[feature].min() <= 0:
                    df_filter[feature] = df_filter[feature]-df_filter[feature].min()+0.01
                df_filter[feature],boxcox_lambda = boxcox(df_filter[feature])
        df_filter = df_filter.merge(emis_df, left_on=['YEAR','MONTH','DAY','HOUR'], right_on=['year','month','day','hour'], how='left')
        df_filter = df_filter.drop(columns=['DATETIME','HOUR','JDAY','YEAR','MONTH','DAY','DAYOFWEEK','year','month','day','hour'])
        emis = df_filter['emisrate']
        df_filter = df_filter.drop(columns=['emisrate'])
        scaler = StandardScaler()
        X = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(df_filter), index=df_filter.index, columns=df_filter.columns)
        for model_type in model_types:
            scores, coefs, y_pred, y_test = create_model(X, emis, model_type)
            test_scores.loc[monitor,model_type+"_R2"] = scores['Test_R2'].values[0]
            if model_type != "NN":
                coefs_dict[model_type+"_"+monitor] = coefs
            y_preds_dict[model_type+"_"+monitor] = y_pred
            y_tests_dict[model_type+"_"+monitor] = y_test
    return test_scores, coefs_dict, y_preds_dict, y_tests_dict

The prediction for aggregated emissions using the top 10% of concentrations measured at the GLM3 station produces the best results. This isn't too surprising, since GLM3 is the closest monitor to the largest emissions source of mystery pollutant "X" (what we're trying to predict). The SO2 UV1 fenceline, GLM2 monitor, and GLM4 monitor are the monitors that are furthest out from the major pollution sources.

Let's look at the emissions predicting using the GLM3 subset in more detail:

Physical insights that we can draw from the ridge coefficients and feature importances:

  • Across all three models, the most important features tend to be dispersion factors originating from S1, S4, and S5, and ending at GLM3 or one of the UV1 fenceline receptors. Recall that a dispersion factor measures the source/strength coupling at any given hour, and is affected by meteorology and terrain - a high dispersion factor means favorable transport from one source to a given receptor. In layman's terms, we should expect a higher emissions prediction when certain dispersion factors are high (i.e., when winds blow from the highest emitting sources towards the monitors), and we should also expect to see an inverse relationship with other dispersion factors (i.e., representative of times when winds blow from the highest emitting sources away from the monitors of interest, towards other monitors in different directions).
  • Example: the ridge regression coefficients show the strongest positive predictor is S4_GLM3, while the strongest negative predictor is S1_GLM3. When S4_GLM3 is high, winds blow from source S4 towards monitor GLM3. S4 is the largest source of mystery pollutant X in the region, so this feature should naturally correlate well with a high emissions prediction. Meanwhile, S1 is a relatively small source of pollutant X, and is on the opposite side of the monitor compared to S4. So when winds blow from S1 to GLM3, the monitors are only seeing a small reading of pollutant X, while larger emissions sources are being blown away from the monitors in a different direction.

Observations:

  • Ridge produces the poorest results, and the trend looks more like a square root than a linear trend. The model also predicts negative values, which is not possible. As mentioned at the beginning the purpose of the ridge model is to observe feature coefficients, not for predictive value.
  • Both tree-based models predict well at lower emissions values, but start to diverge a bit at higher values. Neural networks are somewhat the opposite.
  • Model stacking could produce a better result, and would potentially be a topic of future work. It has not seen much use in the air quality community yet.

Conclusions and Future Work¶

In this project, I was able to build a reasonably good predictor of emissions events corresponding to the top 10% of concentration hits at a given air quality monitor using tree-based models (Random Forests and XGBoost) and neural networks. These models could serve as a much more time-efficient method compared to traditional inverse air quality models. We saw that even without explicit information on concentrations of "mystery pollutant X", we were able to accurately predict aggregated emissions from a variety of different sources in the region.

With more time, I would explore model stacking and model tuning to optimize the models for better prediction. I would also explore other datasets, such as including traffic, rail, or shipping data, which are non-negligible sources of pollutant X.

Due to the non-zero degree of uncertainty with using machine learning for air quality prediciton, it is unlikely that these types of models would gain approval for use by EPA or local air quality agencies. However, many existing air quality data projects use machine learning to predict air quality trends in order to help inform the public of current and upcoming air quality.
